select
  s.id, 'board', NULL, 'ระบบ EMS / professionalism: ethics + informed consent

คำถาม: surgical informed consent + complex situations', '[{"label":"A","text":"Verbal consent sufficient"},{"label":"B","text":"**Informed consent — ethical + legal cornerstone**: (1) **Elements of informed consent**: - **Disclosure**: nature of procedure, indication, risks (material risks), benefits, alternatives (including no treatment), prognosis - **Comprehension**: patient understands (assess with teach-back) - **Voluntariness**: not coerced - **Competence/Capacity**: decision-making capacity present - **Authorization**: explicit consent; (2) **Standards for disclosure** (vary by jurisdiction): - **Professional / reasonable physician**: what a reasonable physician would disclose (older standard) - **Reasonable patient (material risk)**: what a reasonable patient would want to know — modern preferred standard - **Subjective patient**: what this specific patient would want; (3) **Capacity assessment** — 4 components (MacArthur): - Understand information - Appreciate situation + consequences - Reason about options - Communicate choice; (4) **Capacity vs competence**: - Capacity is clinical judgment, decision-specific, fluctuates - Competence is legal determination - Both required for valid consent; (5) **Special situations**: - **Emergency**: implied consent for life-saving treatment when capacity absent + no surrogate available - **Surrogate decision-maker**: legal hierarchy (spouse, adult child, parent, sibling per state law); follow advance directive / patient''s prior expressed wishes (substituted judgment); best interests if no expressed wishes - **Pediatric**: parent / legal guardian; assent of child as developmentally appropriate; exceptions: emancipated minor, mature minor doctrine, specific medical issues (STI, contraception, mental health, substance use depending on jurisdiction) - **Pregnancy**: maternal autonomy paramount; competing fetal interests legally + ethically complex - **Cognitive impairment**: assess capacity decision-by-decision; involve family + surrogate; advance directives - **Jehovah''s Witness + blood refusal**: respect adult capacitated patient; pediatric — court intervention may be needed (best interest of child); document + plan accordingly; (6) **Documentation**: signed consent form + procedure note documenting discussion; teach-back; questions answered; (7) **Refusal of treatment**: equally valid right; document discussion + understanding; offer second opinion + reconsider; counsel of consequences without coercion; (8) **Withdrawal / withholding life-sustaining treatment**: same ethical principle as not initiating; supported by ethics committees, palliative care, legal frameworks; symptom management during withdrawal (opioid + benzodiazepine for dyspnea/anxiety); not euthanasia; (9) **Cultural + religious considerations**: explore + respect; interpreter services; family-centered decision-making in some cultures; (10) **Ethics consultation** for complex/disputed: hospital ethics committee resource; (11) **Conflicts of interest**: disclose; research consent additional layer; IRB oversight"},{"label":"C","text":"Skip discussion of risks"},{"label":"D","text":"Coerce decisions"},{"label":"E","text":"No documentation needed"}]'::jsonb,
  'B', '**Informed Consent** — ethical + legal foundation of surgical practice. Required for all surgical procedures (with limited exceptions like emergent life-saving in unconscious patient). **Four elements**: 1. **Disclosure** — adequate information 2. **Comprehension** — patient understands 3. **Voluntariness** — free of coercion 4. **Authorization** — explicit consent **Disclosure standards** (jurisdiction-dependent): - **Professional / reasonable physician**: traditional — what reasonable physician would disclose - **Material risk / reasonable patient** (Canterbury v. Spence 1972, US): modern preferred — what reasonable patient would want to know; includes common risks + serious uncommon risks - **Subjective patient**: rare — what this particular patient would want **Capacity** — clinical determination, decision-specific, fluctuating: - Understand information - Appreciate situation + consequences - Reason about options - Communicate choice MacArthur Competence Assessment Tool — standardized. **Competence** — legal determination (court). **Special situations**: 1. **Emergency** — implied consent for life-saving in incapacitated patient without available surrogate; treatment to extent reasonable + necessary 2. **Surrogate decision-making** — hierarchy by state law: typically spouse, adult child, parent, sibling, other relative, close friend; follow advance directive if exists; use substituted judgment (what patient would want); best interests if no expressed wishes 3. **Pediatric** — parental consent + age-appropriate assent; emancipated minor, mature minor doctrine, specific conditions (reproductive, mental health, substance use) — varies by state 4. **Cognitive impairment / dementia** — capacity decision-by-decision; advance directives; surrogate 5. **Blood refusal (Jehovah''s Witness)** — adult capacitated patient''s right; pediatric — best interest of child may override (court intervention if needed) 6. **Pregnancy** — maternal autonomy paramount; some legal cases test 7. **Substance use, intoxication** — capacity assessment carefully 8. **Mental illness** — does not equate to incapacity; assess specifically **Refusal of treatment** — same right as consent; document + counsel; not coercion. **Withdrawing / withholding life-sustaining treatment** — ethically same as not initiating; well-established legal + ethical framework; symptom management. **Cultural + religious sensitivity** — interpreter, family involvement, cultural humility. **Ethics consultation** — for complex / disputed cases. **Conflicts of interest** disclosure — relevant to consent (research, financial relationships). **Research consent** — IRB + additional protections (HIPAA, informed consent specific to research).', NULL,
  'easy', 'procedures', 'review',
  'surgery', 'ems_mgmt', 'procedures', 'adult',
  'AMA Code of Medical Ethics; ACS Statement on Principles; Canterbury v. Spence 1972; MacArthur Competence Assessment', 'AI-generated-board-seed', true, 'seeded via Claude Code session (no critique pass)'
