select
  s.id, 'board', NULL, 'ผู้ป่วยอายุ 50 ปี post-bariatric sleeve gastrectomy 5 ปีก่อน — มาด้วยอาการ chronic GERD severe + Barrett''s segment 2 cm + esophagitis grade C; PPI optimal failed; weight regain 15 kg from nadir

คำถาม: complex management', '[{"label":"A","text":"Continue PPI alone forever"},{"label":"B","text":"**Post-sleeve gastrectomy GERD complications + weight regain — multidisciplinary**: (1) **Workup**: - EGD (already done) — confirm Barrett''s, biopsy, exclude dysplasia, anatomic assessment (hiatal hernia, sleeve anatomy) - High-resolution manometry — esophageal motility - 24h pH study off PPI — quantify reflux burden - Barium swallow — anatomy of sleeve + reflux dynamics - Possible gastric emptying study; (2) **GERD post-sleeve mechanism**: - Removal of fundus + LES support + His angle disruption - High intragastric pressure (narrow tube) - Hiatal hernia (often pre-existing) - Stenosis at incisura, twisting of sleeve - Decreased gastric compliance; (3) **Medical optimization**: - High-dose PPI (consider esomeprazole 40 mg BID) - H2 blocker bedtime adjunct - Alginate (Gaviscon Advance) post-meal + bedtime - Lifestyle: weight loss if indicated, head of bed elevation, no late meals, avoid trigger foods - Sucralfate for esophagitis; (4) **Barrett''s surveillance + management**: - EGD with biopsies (Seattle protocol) q3-5 yr no dysplasia, more frequent if dysplasia - Endoscopic ablation (RFA) for dysplasia/intramucosal carcinoma - PPI lifelong; (5) **Revision bariatric surgery options for severe GERD**: - **Conversion to Roux-en-Y gastric bypass (RYGB)** — gold standard for sleeve failure + GERD: eliminates reflux + addresses weight regain + better metabolic outcomes; technically challenging revision - **Magnetic sphincter augmentation (LINX device)** — for selected without hiatal hernia or severe esophagitis; can be done post-sleeve - **Hiatal hernia repair + sleeve adjustment** — if HH primary issue - **Fundoplication impossible** post-sleeve (no fundus); (6) **Weight regain workup** — common after bariatric: - Behavioral (eating habits, portion, snacking, beverages) - Hormonal adaptation (ghrelin recovers, GLP-1 may decrease) - Anatomic (sleeve dilation, gastrogastric fistula) - Psychological (food addiction, binge eating, depression) - Medical (medication weight gain — antidepressants, antipsychotics); (7) **Weight regain management**: - Nutrition + behavioral counseling - Pharmacotherapy: GLP-1 agonists (semaglutide, tirzepatide) — increasingly used post-bariatric; counsel on possible reduced response - Revision surgery if anatomic issue + severe regain - Endoscopic options (re-sleeve, plication) — selected; (8) **Multidisciplinary**: bariatric surgery, GI, nutrition, psychology, primary care; long-term integrated follow-up; (9) **Patient counseling**: realistic expectations, lifelong management"},{"label":"C","text":"Stop all medications"},{"label":"D","text":"Refuse all interventions"},{"label":"E","text":"Discharge home"}]'::jsonb,
  'B', '**Sleeve gastrectomy + GERD** — major issue. Sleeve gastrectomy has GERD as major long-term complication (10-30% develop new or worsened GERD; even higher with longer follow-up). Some develop Barrett''s esophagus (~ 3-15% at 5+ years per cohorts), potentially with dysplasia / adenocarcinoma. **Pre-op evaluation should screen for GERD severity** — patients with severe pre-op GERD may not be ideal sleeve candidates; some advocate RYGB primary for these patients. **Mechanisms of post-sleeve GERD**: 1. Anatomic — disruption of His angle, removal of fundus, reduced LES support 2. Physiologic — high intragastric pressure (narrow tube), reduced compliance 3. Hiatal hernia (pre-existing or new) 4. Sleeve anatomy issues — stenosis at incisura, twist, dilated proximal pouch 5. Delayed gastric emptying **Management ladder**: 1. **Medical optimization**: high-dose PPI (potentially BID), H2 blocker adjunct, alginate, lifestyle, weight management 2. **EGD with Barrett''s surveillance**: Seattle protocol biopsies; treat dysplasia (RFA/EMR) 3. **Workup**: manometry, pH study, barium swallow, gastric emptying 4. **Surgical revision** for refractory: - **Conversion to RYGB** — most effective for GERD + addresses weight regain; complex revision but acceptable outcomes - **LINX (magnetic sphincter augmentation)** — selected without severe esophagitis or large hiatal hernia; preserves anatomy - **Hiatal hernia repair** if primary anatomic issue 5. **Fundoplication NOT possible** post-sleeve (no fundus available) **Weight regain post-bariatric** — common (20-40% at 10 yr): - Behavioral + dietary - Hormonal adaptation - Anatomic (sleeve dilation, gastrogastric fistula in RYGB) - Psychological - Medication weight gain Management: behavioral counseling, nutrition support, GLP-1 + dual agonists (semaglutide 2.4 mg, tirzepatide 15 mg increasingly used post-bariatric with good response in many), revision surgery for anatomic issue + severe regain, endoscopic options (re-sleeve, plication). **GLP-1 + GIP/GLP-1 dual agonists post-bariatric**: increasingly utilized for weight regain or insufficient initial response; semaglutide (Wegovy, Ozempic), tirzepatide (Mounjaro/Zepbound); response variable but many achieve meaningful additional weight loss; long-term data accumulating. **Multidisciplinary lifelong care** — essential for bariatric patient; integrate medical, surgical, nutritional, psychological, behavioral approaches.', NULL,
  'hard', 'gi', 'review',
  'surgery', 'integrative', 'gi', 'adult',
  'ASMBS Position Statements on Revisional Bariatric; SAGES Guidelines; Felsenreich DM et al. Obes Surg', 'AI-generated-board-seed', true, 'seeded via Claude Code session (no critique pass)'
from public.mcq_subjects s
where s.name = 'surg_integrative'
