select
  s.id, 'board', NULL, 'ชายไทยอายุ 55 ปี smoker, COPD GOLD C, ผ่า lung transplant 6 weeks ago — มา ED ด้วยอาการ shortness of breath progressive 3 days + fever 38.4°C + cough + decreased exercise tolerance

VS: BP 124/78, HR 102, RR 24, SpO2 88% room air
CXR: bilateral infiltrates new vs prior baseline
Lab: WBC 14,400 (was 8,000), Cr 1.4 (baseline 1.0), tacrolimus level 12 ng/mL (target 10-15)

คำถาม: differential + workup', '[{"label":"A","text":"Antibiotic alone outpatient"},{"label":"B","text":"**Post-lung transplant respiratory deterioration — broad differential, expedited workup**: (1) **Differential**: - **Acute rejection** (most common cause of decline first 6 mo) - cellular (T-cell mediated) more common than antibody-mediated - Diagnosis: bronchoscopy + transbronchial biopsy (gold standard) - Treatment: pulse steroid (methylprednisolone 1 g × 3 days), augment immunosuppression; ATG/rituximab for severe/AMR - **Infection** (also common): - CMV (q month surveillance for first 6-12 mo); treat valganciclovir/ganciclovir - PJP (Pneumocystis jirovecii — prophylaxis TMP-SMX, dapsone if intolerant); treat high-dose TMP-SMX + steroid - Fungal (Aspergillus most concerning in lung transplant) — voriconazole, posaconazole - Bacterial pneumonia (community + nosocomial) — culture-directed antibiotic - Atypical (Mycoplasma, Legionella, Chlamydia) - **Reperfusion injury / primary graft dysfunction** — usually earlier (< 72h post-transplant) - **Airway complications**: anastomotic dehiscence, stenosis, malacia — bronchoscopy + intervention - **Pulmonary embolism** — high risk post-major surgery + hypercoagulable - **Cardiac**: rejection if heart transplant component, fluid overload - **Drug toxicity**: tacrolimus, mycophenolate, sirolimus pulmonary toxicity; (2) **Workup**: - CBC + diff, BMP, LFT, lactate, troponin, BNP - Respiratory cultures (sputum, bronchoscopy with BAL — culture for bacteria, virus, fungus, AFB) - CMV PCR (blood), galactomannan (Aspergillus), β-D-glucan - Tacrolimus + other drug levels (already checked — therapeutic) - ABG - CXR + CT chest with contrast (if Cr permits) - ECG, echo if cardiac concern - Bronchoscopy + transbronchial biopsy — for rejection vs infection; (3) **Empiric treatment** while workup in progress: - Broad-spectrum antibiotic (cefepime + vancomycin) - Antifungal if high risk (voriconazole) - CMV antiviral if suspected - Consider pulse steroid if rejection strongly suspected after infection ruled out; (4) **Multidisciplinary**: transplant pulmonology, ID, surgery, ICU; (5) **Long-term**: rejection prophylaxis (immunosuppression adherence, drug levels), infection prophylaxis (PJP, CMV, fungal), surveillance bronchoscopies, pulmonary rehab, vaccinations (inactivated), lifestyle"},{"label":"C","text":"Increase immunosuppression empirically"},{"label":"D","text":"Outpatient observation"},{"label":"E","text":"Stop all medications"}]'::jsonb,
  'B', '**Post-lung transplant respiratory deterioration** — broad differential; rejection + infection top considerations; both can overlap; biopsy often needed to distinguish. **Common causes by time after transplant**: - **< 30 days**: primary graft dysfunction, bacterial pneumonia, anastomotic issues, hyperacute rejection (rare with cross-match) - **30 days - 6 months**: acute cellular rejection peak, CMV, PJP (if not on prophylaxis), bacterial, Aspergillus, herpes - **6 months - 1 year**: late acute rejection, chronic rejection emerging (BOS — bronchiolitis obliterans syndrome / CLAD — chronic lung allograft dysfunction), community-acquired infections, CMV later if no prophylaxis - **> 1 year**: chronic rejection (CLAD/BOS) main long-term threat, infections, malignancy (PTLD, skin) **Acute rejection**: - **Cellular** (T-cell mediated) — more common; bronchoscopy + transbronchial biopsy (grading A0-A4 per ISHLT) - **Antibody-mediated (AMR)** — emerging recognition; DSA + biopsy with C4d staining; harder to diagnose **Bronchoscopy with BAL + transbronchial biopsy** — gold standard for: - Distinguishing rejection from infection - Identifying specific pathogen - Quantifying inflammation - Surveillance bronchoscopies routine first year **Common infections post-lung transplant**: 1. **CMV** — common; PCR surveillance; valganciclovir/ganciclovir prophylaxis + treatment 2. **PJP (P. jirovecii)** — TMP-SMX prophylaxis lifelong; high-dose TMP-SMX + steroid for treatment 3. **Aspergillus** — voriconazole prophylaxis often in early post-transplant; treatment voriconazole / isavuconazole / amphotericin 4. **Bacterial** — culture-directed; nosocomial vs community 5. **HSV / VZV / EBV (PTLD)** — antiviral prophylaxis (acyclovir/valacyclovir) **Chronic Lung Allograft Dysfunction (CLAD)** — main barrier to long-term survival post-lung transplant: - Bronchiolitis Obliterans Syndrome (BOS) — obstructive - Restrictive Allograft Syndrome (RAS) - 50% by 5 yr; limits long-term survival - Treatment options limited; some response to azithromycin (motility, anti-inflammatory), extracorporeal photopheresis, montelukast; re-transplantation in selected **Empiric treatment** while workup pending: balance treating likely conditions while waiting for tissue diagnosis; multidisciplinary team essential. **Drug interactions** — extensive: azoles (fluconazole, voriconazole, posaconazole) interact with calcineurin inhibitors (tacrolimus, cyclosporine) — increase levels; dose-adjust + monitor closely.', NULL,
  'hard', 'id', 'review',
  'surgery', 'clinical_decision', 'id', 'elderly',
  'ISHLT Lung Transplant Guidelines; AST/ASTS Lung Transplant Guidelines; Greer M et al. Curr Opin Organ Transplant', 'AI-generated-board-seed', true, 'seeded via Claude Code session (no critique pass)'
from public.mcq_subjects s
where s.name = 'surg_clinical_decision'
  and s.audience = 'board'
  and not exists (
    select 1 from public.mcq_questions q
    where q.exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
      and q.board_specialty = 'surgery'
      and q.scenario = 'ชายไทยอายุ 55 ปี smoker, COPD GOLD C, ผ่า lung transplant 6 weeks ago — มา ED ด้วยอาการ shortness of breath progressive 3 days + fever 38.4°C + cough + decreased exercise tolerance

VS: BP 124/78, HR 102, RR 24, SpO2 88% room air
CXR: bilateral infiltrates new vs prior baseline
Lab: WBC 14,400 (was 8,000), Cr 1.4 (baseline 1.0), tacrolimus level 12 ng/mL (target 10-15)

คำถาม: differential + workup'
  );

