select
  s.id, 'board', NULL, 'ชายไทยอายุ 60 ปี ผ่า bypass graft femoropopliteal 2 weeks ago — มา ED ด้วยอาการ persistent leg swelling + pain + increasing erythema along graft site + draining wound + ไข้

VS: BP 116/72, HR 102, Temp 38.6°C
Leg: surgical wound erythema + drainage purulent; calf swollen; pulse intact distally
Lab: WBC 16,400, CRP 180
Blood culture: gram-positive cocci
CT angiogram: fluid + air around prosthetic graft; no acute occlusion; perigraft abscess

คำถาม: management', '[{"label":"A","text":"Antibiotic alone"},{"label":"B","text":"**Prosthetic graft infection — surgical emergency requires combined antimicrobial + surgical management**: (1) **Vascular graft infection (early < 4 mo more severe; late >4 mo possibly less severe but chronic)**; (2) **Initial workup**: blood cultures + wound culture + tissue cultures + CT angiography (perigraft fluid/gas/abscess, anastomotic pseudoaneurysm); (3) **IV broad-spectrum antibiotic** — cover staph (incl MRSA), gram-negative — empiric vancomycin + cefepime or pip-tazo; tailor per culture; long course (6 weeks IV + 6 weeks oral suppression often; lifelong oral if cannot remove graft); (4) **Surgical management options** by severity + extent: - **Graft excision + extra-anatomic bypass** — gold standard for severe infection of prosthetic graft (e.g., axillobifemoral bypass for aortobifemoral graft infection); ''remove infection, reroute flow'' - **In-situ replacement with autologous vein** (femoral vein, GSV, cryopreserved) — for selected (lower infection burden, anatomy suitable, organism less virulent) - **In-situ replacement with new prosthetic / rifampin-soaked prosthetic** — controversial, less infection burden, soft-tissue coverage; selected - **Local debridement + irrigation + muscle flap coverage + retained graft** — selected (low-virulence, localized, no anastomosis involvement); risk of recurrence - **Suppressive antibiotic alone** — if graft cannot be safely removed (elderly, prohibitive surgery) — chronic infection accepted; (5) **Multidisciplinary**: vascular surgery, ID, plastic surgery (flaps), wound care; (6) **Limb salvage** consideration if graft removal compromises perfusion → bypass first to preserve limb then address infection; (7) **Prevention**: meticulous technique, prophylactic antibiotic, avoid groin incision when feasible (high infection rate), tunnel away from skin, treat infections elsewhere pre-op, glycemic control, smoking cessation"},{"label":"C","text":"Outpatient management"},{"label":"D","text":"Amputation immediately"},{"label":"E","text":"Wait for resolution"}]'::jsonb,
  'B', '**Vascular graft infection** — 1-5% incidence; mortality 10-25%; limb loss 10-20%. **Classification**: - **Szilagyi**: I — skin only; II — subcutaneous; III — graft involvement - **Samson**: I-V — granular detail of extent - **Early (< 4 mo)**: more virulent, sepsis common, often Staph - **Late (> 4 mo)**: indolent, low-virulence organisms (coag-neg Staph), chronic sinus tract **Imaging**: - CT angiography — perigraft fluid, gas, abscess, pseudoaneurysm, aortoenteric fistula - PET-CT — infection localization (high sensitivity) - WBC scan **Management principles**: 1. **Antibiotic** — broad-spectrum + culture-directed; long duration 2. **Surgery** — usually graft removal + revascularization 3. **Extra-anatomic bypass** — definitive for severe (e.g., axillobifem for aortic graft infection) 4. **In-situ replacement** — autologous vein (femoral or GSV) or cryopreserved arterial; or rifampin-soaked prosthetic in selected 5. **Selected conservative** — debridement + flap + retain graft for low-virulence, localized **Aortoenteric fistula** — feared complication of aortic graft infection — bleed from GI tract (small hemorrhage ''herald bleed'' before catastrophic); emergency. **Prevention**: aseptic technique, antibiotic prophylaxis (cefazolin pre-incision, redose long surgery), groin avoidance when possible (high infection — alternatives like extraperitoneal access), wound closure, glycemic control, smoking cessation, MRSA decolonization in high-risk. **Long-term**: lifelong oral antibiotic suppression in selected (cannot remove graft + chronic low-grade infection); surveillance for recurrence + complications.', NULL,
  'hard', 'vascular', 'review',
  'surgery', 'clinical_decision', 'vascular', 'elderly',
  'SVS Vascular Graft Infection; ESVS Chronic Limb-Threatening Ischemia; FitzGerald SF et al. Eur J Vasc Endovasc Surg', 'AI-generated-board-seed', true, 'seeded via Claude Code session (no critique pass)'
from public.mcq_subjects s
where s.name = 'surg_clinical_decision'
