select
  s.id, 'board', NULL, 'เด็กชายอายุ 3 ปี ผ้าปูเตียงพันคอเล่นกัน — ตื่นมาภาวะสุดเย็น ครอบครัวพบในห้องไม่ตอบสนอง + นำส่ง ER

VS: not breathing, pulseless, asystole on monitor
Family started CPR + 911 — ETA 8 min

คำถาม: pediatric cardiac arrest + resuscitation', '[{"label":"A","text":"Stop resuscitation immediately"},{"label":"B","text":"**Pediatric cardiac arrest — PALS protocol with airway emphasis (often respiratory etiology in children)**: (1) **Most pediatric arrest is respiratory in origin** (asphyxia, drowning, choking, sepsis) — different from adult primary cardiac; (2) **Immediate steps**: - Bystander/EMS high-quality CPR (chest compressions 100-120/min, depth 1/3 AP diameter — 4 cm infant, 5 cm child, 5-6 cm adolescent) - Coordinated compressions:breaths 30:2 (single rescuer) or 15:2 (2 rescuers child) - Early effective ventilation critical - Automated external defibrillator (AED) — pediatric pads/attenuator for < 25 kg or < 8 yr (use adult if pediatric not available) - Defibrillation for shockable rhythms (VF/VT) — 2 J/kg first shock, 4 J/kg subsequent; (3) **In hospital**: - Continue compressions - Secure airway: bag-mask first (effective oxygenation often), advanced airway (ET tube, supraglottic) when feasible - IV access (peripheral or intraosseous — IO is fast + reliable in pediatric, especially when peripheral difficult) - **Epinephrine** 0.01 mg/kg IV/IO q3-5 min - **Amiodarone** 5 mg/kg IV/IO for VF/VT (after 3rd shock); lidocaine alternative - Treat reversible causes (H''s + T''s): hypoxia, hypovolemia, hydrogen ion (acidosis), hypo/hyperkalemia, hypothermia, hypoglycemia, toxins, tamponade, tension pneumo, thrombosis (PE, coronary), trauma; (4) **Post-cardiac arrest care (PALS)**: - Targeted temperature management — pediatric: maintain normothermia or therapeutic hypothermia (32-34°C × 48h then rewarm) per THAPCA pediatric trials (modest benefit/equipoise) - Oxygenation target SpO2 94-99% - Hemodynamic optimization - Neurological assessment + supportive care - Identify + treat underlying cause - Family support, psychosocial; (5) **Strangulation / hanging-specific**: - Cervical spine immobilization (potential injury) - Airway: edema common, may need surgical airway; ENT consult - CT brain + cervical spine when stable - Neuro-protective care + neurological prognostication; (6) **Outcomes**: - Pediatric in-hospital arrest survival ~ 30-50% to discharge (better than adult) - Out-of-hospital pediatric ~ 10-15% survival - Neurological outcome variable; (7) **Trauma resuscitation considerations**: TXA in massive bleeding (pediatric dose 15 mg/kg max 1 g), blood products, surgical bleeding control; (8) **Family presence** during resuscitation — supported by AHA + pediatric guidelines — improves family coping"},{"label":"C","text":"Discharge home"},{"label":"D","text":"Surgery alone"},{"label":"E","text":"Wait without intervention"}]'::jsonb,
  'B', '**Pediatric cardiac arrest** — distinct from adult: 1. **Etiology**: respiratory most common (asphyxia, drowning, choking, sepsis, SIDS) vs adult primary cardiac (VF) 2. **Airway + ventilation early + effective** — central to pediatric resuscitation 3. **PALS** (Pediatric Advanced Life Support) — AHA algorithm **Key differences from adult ACLS**: - Compression depth: 1/3 AP diameter (4 cm infant, 5 cm child, 5-6 cm adolescent) - Compression:Ventilation ratio: 30:2 single rescuer, 15:2 two rescuers (child); adult always 30:2 - Defibrillation: 2 J/kg first, 4 J/kg subsequent; pediatric pads/attenuator < 25 kg if available - Drug dosing weight-based - Epinephrine 0.01 mg/kg IV/IO - Amiodarone 5 mg/kg IV/IO for VF/VT - IO access common (fast, reliable, equivalent to IV) **H''s + T''s** (reversible causes): hypoxia, hypovolemia, hydrogen (acidosis), hypo/hyperkalemia, hypothermia, hypoglycemia, toxins, tamponade, tension pneumothorax, thrombosis (PE, coronary), trauma. **Post-arrest care (PALS)**: - Targeted temperature management — pediatric: THAPCA trials show no clear benefit of hypothermia 32-34°C vs normothermia 36-37.5°C; either acceptable - Avoid hyperthermia (fever post-arrest worsens outcomes) - Oxygen target 94-99% (avoid hyperoxia) - Hemodynamic, neurological support **Strangulation/hanging-specific considerations**: cervical spine injury, airway edema (may need surgical airway), CT imaging, neuroprotective care. **Trauma**: TXA (15 mg/kg max 1 g pediatric), blood products, surgical control. **Family presence during resuscitation**: increasingly supported (AHA, pediatric guidelines) — improves family coping + closure. **Outcomes**: pediatric in-hospital arrest ~ 30-50% survival to discharge (better than adult); out-of-hospital ~ 10-15%. Variable neurological outcome — depends on cause, downtime, witnessed status, bystander CPR.', NULL,
  'hard', 'pediatrics', 'review',
  'surgery', 'clinical_decision', 'pediatrics', 'child',
