select
  s.id, 'board', NULL, 'ระบบ EMS / ethics: organ donation

คำถาม: organ donation + end-of-life', '[{"label":"A","text":"Avoid all organ donation discussions"},{"label":"B","text":"**Organ donation — modern approach**: (1) **Types of donation**: a. **Deceased donor**: - **Donation after brain death (DBD)** — most common - **Donation after circulatory death (DCD)** — increasing globally - **Tissue donation** — corneas, skin, bone, heart valves — wide donor pool (vs solid organ stricter); b. **Living donor** — kidney (most common), liver lobe, lung lobe, small bowel segment, pancreas segment; (2) **Brain death determination**: - Clinical criteria (irreversible cessation of all brain function): - Cause of coma known + irreversible - Absence of confounders (hypothermia, drugs, metabolic) - Coma without response - Absent brainstem reflexes (pupillary, corneal, vestibulo-ocular, gag, cough) - Apnea test positive (no respiratory drive with PaCO2 > 60) - Confirmatory tests if needed (EEG, cerebral blood flow study, brain death angiogram); (3) **DCD (Donation after Circulatory Death)**: - Donor not brain-dead but has irrecoverable injury + decision to withdraw life support - Withdrawal in OR or ICU; declaration of death after circulatory cessation (5 min asystole typical) - Warm ischemia time minimized for organ recovery - Expanding donor pool — outcomes good in selected (kidney, liver, lung, heart with NRP — normothermic regional perfusion); (4) **Organ procurement organizations (OPO)**: - Coordinate donor evaluation + family approach + organ allocation - Independent from medical team caring for potential donor (separation of duties); (5) **Family approach** — best practice: - Compassionate, after death declaration / family understanding of prognosis - Specialized requesters (OPO coordinators) trained - Right to refuse respected; not coerced - Discuss patient''s wishes (donor card, advance directive, organ donor registry); (6) **Consent**: - Opt-in (most countries — US) — explicit consent required - Opt-out (presumed consent — Spain, Austria, others) — higher donor rates - Family may override registered donor wishes (varies by jurisdiction); (7) **Allocation**: - UNOS / OPTN in US (similar systems globally — Eurotransplant, Australia/NZ ANZDATA, etc.) - Algorithms balance: medical urgency, time on list, blood type/HLA matching, geographic distance, pediatric priority - Special considerations: HCC exception (MELD), Status 1A for fulminant liver failure, etc.; (8) **Living donor**: - Evaluation: medical, psychological, social, financial - Donor advocate / independent assessment - Risks: surgical complications, long-term (kidney function decline modest, but lifelong follow-up needed) - Donor protection — primary goal; (9) **Special situations**: - Anencephalic newborn donation — controversial - Death by neurologic criteria in children - Pregnant donor; (10) **Increase donation**: - Public education + awareness - Family discussions - Donor registry - Required request laws - Routine notification of OPO - Donor management protocols; (11) **Ethics**: separation of donor + recipient care teams, dead donor rule, no payment for organs (with limited exceptions in some countries), pediatric considerations"},{"label":"C","text":"Sell organs commercially"},{"label":"D","text":"Avoid family input"},{"label":"E","text":"No regulation needed"}]'::jsonb,
  'B', '**Organ donation** — central to transplantation; complex ethical, legal, medical framework. **Types**: 1. **Deceased donor**: - DBD (Donation after Brain Death) - most common - DCD (Donation after Circulatory Death) - increasing 2. **Living donor**: kidney (most common), liver lobe, lung lobe, others 3. **Tissue donation**: corneas, skin, bone, heart valves **Brain death** (death by neurologic criteria): - Cause of coma known + irreversible - Confounders excluded (hypothermia, drugs, severe metabolic) - Clinical exam: coma, absent brainstem reflexes, positive apnea test - Confirmatory studies as needed (EEG, cerebral blood flow, angiogram) - Uniform Determination of Death Act (US) + similar laws globally **DCD**: - Maastricht categories I-V (controlled vs uncontrolled) - Withdrawal of life support → asystole → declaration of death (typically 5 min observation) → rapid organ recovery - Warm ischemia time critical for organ viability - Expanding pool — outcomes good for kidney + liver; recently good for heart + lung with NRP (Normothermic Regional Perfusion) **Living donation**: - Kidney most common (~ 30-40% of US transplants) - Liver lobe (right or left lobe — adult-to-adult, left lateral segment adult-to-child) - Donor evaluation comprehensive — medical, psychological, social, financial - Independent donor advocate - Long-term donor follow-up + outcomes tracking - Slight increase in long-term ESRD risk in kidney donors (still low absolute risk) **Ethical principles**: 1. Dead donor rule — vital organs only from confirmed dead 2. Voluntary consent — no coercion, no payment 3. Separation of teams — donor care team independent from recipient/transplant 4. Family approach by OPO + sensitive 5. Equitable allocation 6. Respect for autonomy + patient wishes **Donor management**: aggressive resuscitation post-brain death → optimize organ function for procurement (hemodynamic, hormonal — thyroid, steroid; lung protective ventilation; glycemic control). **OPO + OPTN/UNOS** (US): coordinate, allocate, regulate. **Increasing donation strategies**: opt-out systems (Spain has highest donor rates globally), public education, family discussions, donor registry awareness, required request laws, hospital protocols. **Newer**: extended criteria donor (ECD), hepatitis C+ donor to + recipient with subsequent DAA cure, paired exchange (living kidney swap), domino transplant.', NULL,
  'easy', 'procedures', 'review',
  'surgery', 'ems_mgmt', 'procedures', 'adult',
  'UNOS/OPTN Policies; Uniform Determination of Death Act; AAN Brain Death Criteria 2010 + 2023 Update; AST/ASTS', 'AI-generated-board-seed', true, 'seeded via Claude Code session (no critique pass)'
