select
  s.id, 'board', NULL, 'Integrative: pediatric cancer + survivorship

คำถาม: childhood cancer survivor — long-term care', '[{"label":"A","text":"Same care as adult"},{"label":"B","text":"**Childhood cancer survivorship — multidisciplinary long-term care**: (1) **Background**: - > 85% of childhood cancers cured with modern therapy - > 500,000 childhood cancer survivors in US alone, growing - Late effects significant — 60-80% have at least one chronic health condition by 30 years post-diagnosis (CCSS data); (2) **Late effects of cancer + treatment**: a. **Cardiac**: - Anthracycline cardiotoxicity (doxorubicin, daunorubicin) — dose-dependent; cardiomyopathy, HF; echo surveillance based on cumulative dose + RT + age - Radiation cardiomyopathy + valve disease + coronary disease (mediastinal RT) - Hypertension + dyslipidemia b. **Pulmonary**: - Bleomycin pulmonary toxicity - Radiation pneumonitis + fibrosis - Restrictive disease post chest RT/surgery c. **Endocrine**: - Hypothyroidism (RT or chemo) - Growth hormone deficiency (cranial RT) - Adrenal insufficiency - Gonadal failure / infertility - DM (steroid, RT — abdomen/pancreas) d. **Reproductive + fertility**: - Premature ovarian failure - Azoospermia / oligospermia (alkylating agent, RT) - Fertility preservation pre-treatment increasingly emphasized (sperm banking, oocyte/embryo cryopreservation, ovarian/testicular tissue) - Increased pregnancy + neonatal complications e. **Secondary malignancies**: - Higher risk lifelong - RT-related (sarcoma, thyroid, breast) - Chemo-related (especially alkylators — AML/MDS) - Surveillance critical f. **Neurocognitive**: - Cranial RT, intrathecal chemo - Learning disabilities, attention, memory, executive function - School + vocational accommodations - Increasingly mitigated with reduced-intensity RT g. **Psychosocial**: - PTSD, anxiety, depression - Body image (amputation, hair loss, scars) - Social/relationship impact h. **Other**: - Cataract (steroid, RT) - Hearing loss (cisplatin, RT) - Osteoporosis - Renal dysfunction - GI/hepatic (HCV — older transfusion, methotrexate hepatotoxicity, RT enteritis) - Dental (RT) - Lymphedema (limb-sparing surgery, lymph node dissection); (3) **Children''s Oncology Group (COG) Long-Term Follow-Up Guidelines** — comprehensive surveillance recommendations by exposure: - Risk-based individualized - Annual visits at least - Modality-specific (anthracycline → echo; RT chest → mammogram early; cisplatin → audio; etc.); (4) **Transition to adult care**: - Pediatric → adult survivorship clinic - Survivorship care plan (treatment summary + future surveillance + late effects + lifestyle) - Patient + family education - Maintain medical records lifelong; (5) **Lifestyle counseling**: - Avoid smoking + heavy alcohol (additive late effect risk) - Healthy diet, exercise, weight - Sun protection (skin Ca risk) - Reproductive counseling + contraception during fertility window; (6) **Vaccinations** — update; post-HCT additional series; live vaccines may be safe later (re-immunization protocols); (7) **Mental health + psychosocial** support throughout life; (8) **Genetic counseling** — increasing recognition of cancer predisposition syndromes in pediatric cancer; testing for selected (Li-Fraumeni, others); (9) **Multidisciplinary** survivorship clinic ideal — oncology, endocrinology, cardiology, GI, neuropsych, fertility, dental, social work, child life (transition); (10) **Quality of life > survival alone** — modern emphasis: late-effect reduction with reduced therapy intensity (e.g., reduced RT dose/volume + chemo de-escalation in ALL based on risk stratification)"},{"label":"C","text":"Discharge after treatment"},{"label":"D","text":"Avoid follow-up"},{"label":"E","text":"Single specialty care"}]'::jsonb,
  'B', '**Childhood cancer survivorship** — > 85% cure rate modern era → growing population of survivors needing long-term care. **CCSS (Childhood Cancer Survivor Study)** large cohort data: > 60-80% chronic health conditions, > 25% severe/life-threatening by 30 years; relative mortality 8× general population (mostly second cancers + cardiac). **Treatment-related late effects** organized by exposure: 1. **Anthracycline cardiotoxicity** — dose-dependent (cumulative > 250-300 mg/m² high risk); baseline + serial echo; risk increased with RT + younger age + female + obesity; dexrazoxane for prevention 2. **Radiation effects** by site + dose: - Chest RT → cardiomyopathy, breast Ca, lung dysfunction, thyroid - Cranial RT → cognitive, growth hormone deficiency, second brain tumor, cataract, stroke - Abdominal RT → renal, gonadal, GI, hepatic, second cancer, lymphatic - Pelvic RT → infertility, second cancer (bladder, colon), lymphedema 3. **Alkylating agents (cyclophosphamide, ifosfamide)** → infertility, secondary AML/MDS 4. **Platinum** → ototoxicity (cisplatin), nephrotoxicity 5. **Methotrexate** intrathecal → cognitive impact 6. **Steroids** → osteoporosis, AVN, cataract, DM 7. **Stem cell transplant** → multiple systems **COG Long-Term Follow-Up Guidelines** — exposure-based + risk-based surveillance recommendations: - Anthracycline → echo q1-5 yr based on dose + RT + age - Chest RT → mammogram + MRI from age 25 or 8 yr post-RT - Cisplatin → audiogram - Cranial RT → cognitive + endocrine - Pelvic/abdominal RT → renal, gonadal, GI Updated periodically; freely available. **Fertility preservation** — increasingly emphasized + offered pre-treatment: - Sperm banking - Oocyte / embryo cryopreservation - Ovarian / testicular tissue cryopreservation (experimental in pre-pubertal — improving) - GnRH agonist during chemo (controversial) **Transition to adult care** — vulnerable period; structured transition essential. Survivorship Care Plan: treatment summary + future surveillance + late effects + lifestyle + contacts. **Multidisciplinary survivorship clinic** — pediatric or transition; ongoing patient + family education + advocacy. **Second cancer surveillance** — lifelong + risk-based; modifiable risk factors (smoking, sun, weight, alcohol). **Mental health + psychosocial** — chronic; PTSD, anxiety, depression elevated in survivors + caregivers + siblings (caregivers often have more PTSD than survivors themselves). **Modern de-escalation** — based on improved risk stratification, biomarkers + targeted therapy → reducing late effect burden while maintaining cure; e.g., modern ALL therapy reduces cranial RT in many; reduce anthracycline; sparing radiation in some Hodgkin protocols.', NULL,
  'hard', 'pediatrics', 'review',
  'surgery', 'integrative', 'pediatrics', 'child',
  'COG Long-Term Follow-Up Guidelines; Childhood Cancer Survivor Study (CCSS); NCCN Survivorship', 'AI-generated-board-seed', true, 'seeded via Claude Code session (no critique pass)'
