select
  s.id, 'board', NULL, 'Clinical: pediatric tumors

คำถาม: pediatric solid tumors — surgical management', '[{"label":"A","text":"Same as adult oncology"},{"label":"B","text":"**Pediatric solid tumors — distinct from adult**: (1) **Common pediatric tumors**: a. **Neuroblastoma** (most common extracranial solid tumor in children): - Arises from neural crest (sympathetic ganglia, adrenal medulla) - Median age 18 months - Catecholamines (urine VMA, HVA) elevated - INRGSS staging (L1, L2, M, MS) - Risk stratification by age + MYCN amplification + ploidy + histology - Treatment by risk: low — observation or surgery alone; intermediate — chemo + surgery; high — multimodal (chemo + surgery + RT + immunotherapy + transplant) - Anti-GD2 immunotherapy (dinutuximab) for high-risk maintenance b. **Wilms tumor (nephroblastoma)** — most common renal in children: - Median age 3 yr - Triphasic histology - Associations: WAGR syndrome, Beckwith-Wiedemann, Denys-Drash, hemihypertrophy - Bilateral 5-10% - SIOP vs COG protocols (neoadjuvant chemo vs upfront nephrectomy) - Survival > 90% favorable histology - Nephron-sparing in bilateral / high-risk c. **Rhabdomyosarcoma** — most common pediatric soft tissue sarcoma: - Embryonal (most common) > alveolar > pleomorphic > spindle - Sites: head/neck, GU (bladder, prostate), extremity, trunk - Multimodal: chemo + surgery + RT - Outcomes by risk d. **Hepatoblastoma** — most common liver tumor in children: - Median age 1-3 yr - AFP marker - PRETEXT staging - Neoadjuvant cisplatin-based chemo + surgical resection (often hepatectomy or transplant if extensive) - Survival ~ 80% e. **Ewing sarcoma** — bone (+ extraosseous): - Translocation EWSR1-FLI1 - Multimodal: chemo + local control (surgery + RT) f. **Osteosarcoma** — most common primary bone tumor: - Adolescent, distal femur > proximal tibia > proximal humerus - Neoadjuvant chemo + limb-sparing surgery + adjuvant chemo - Outcomes ~ 70% localized g. **Retinoblastoma** — most common pediatric intraocular: - RB1 gene; familial + sporadic - Younger age (median 1-2 yr) - Treatment: chemo (intra-arterial increasingly used), focal therapy, enucleation for severe - Second malignancy risk lifelong (especially RB1 germline — osteosarcoma, others) h. **Germ cell tumors** — testicular, ovarian, extragonadal: - AFP + β-hCG markers - Multimodal i. **CNS tumors** — most common pediatric cancer overall: medulloblastoma, ependymoma, glioma, ATRT, craniopharyngioma — pediatric neurosurgery + oncology - Reduced-dose RT + targeted chemo in modern era; (2) **Pediatric oncology multidisciplinary**: pediatric oncology, pediatric surgery, radiation oncology, pathology, radiology, child life, social work, psychology, nutrition, school liaison; (3) **Clinical trial enrollment** — high participation rate in pediatric (much higher than adult) — drives outcome improvements; (4) **COG (Children''s Oncology Group)** — coordinates research + trials globally; (5) **Treatment modifications** for child: - Surgical technique - Chemotherapy dose by body surface area or weight - Radiation considerations (developing tissues — late effects) - Anesthesia + perioperative considerations - Psychological + family support - Long-term follow-up + late effects; (6) **Tumor biology** often distinct from adult — pediatric cancers have different driver mutations, fewer mutations overall, often single translocations or copy number changes; (7) **Survival** has improved dramatically — > 85% 5-yr survival modern era for childhood cancer overall (selected types — ALL ~ 90%, Wilms 90%+, retinoblastoma 95%+; brain tumors more variable; high-risk neuroblastoma + sarcomas + AML more challenging)"},{"label":"C","text":"No surgery in pediatric tumors"},{"label":"D","text":"Single modality treatment"},{"label":"E","text":"Adult dosing for chemo"}]'::jsonb,
  'B', '**Pediatric solid tumors** — distinct from adult cancers in biology, behavior, treatment, outcomes. Childhood cancer overall now > 85% 5-yr survival; substantial late-effect concern. **Major pediatric solid tumors**: 1. **Neuroblastoma** — most common extracranial solid tumor in children; neural crest origin (adrenal, paraspinal sympathetic); median age 18 mo; presentation variable (mass, neuro symptoms, paraneoplastic — opsoclonus-myoclonus). INRGSS staging + risk groups (low/intermediate/high based on age + MYCN + ploidy + histology + others). High-risk treatment: induction chemo → surgery → high-dose chemo + autologous stem cell rescue (sometimes tandem) → RT to primary → maintenance with retinoic acid + anti-GD2 immunotherapy (dinutuximab) — improves survival. Stage MS (infant with skin/liver/marrow involvement) may spontaneously regress in selected. 2. **Wilms tumor** — most common pediatric renal; median 3 yr; SIOP (neoadjuvant chemo before nephrectomy) vs COG (upfront nephrectomy then chemo) — both with > 90% survival favorable histology. Bilateral 5-10% — nephron-sparing emphasis. Anaplastic histology worse prognosis. 3. **Rhabdomyosarcoma (RMS)** — most common pediatric soft tissue sarcoma; embryonal most common (favorable), alveolar worse (PAX3/7-FOXO1 translocation). Sites: head/neck (orbital + parameningeal + non-parameningeal), GU (bladder, prostate, paratesticular, vulva/vagina), extremity, trunk. Multimodal — chemo (VAC backbone) + surgery + RT. 4. **Hepatoblastoma** — most common pediatric liver tumor; AFP marker; PRETEXT staging guides resectability + neoadjuvant chemo + surgery (hepatectomy or transplant if extensive). ~ 80% cure. 5. **Ewing sarcoma** — bone + extraosseous; small round blue cell; EWSR1-FLI1 translocation. Multimodal. 6. **Osteosarcoma** — most common primary bone tumor; adolescent; distal femur most common; neoadjuvant chemo + limb-sparing surgery; ~ 70% cure if localized. 7. **Retinoblastoma** — most common pediatric intraocular; RB1 (Knudson 2-hit); familial (germline — bilateral, multifocal, second cancer risk lifelong) vs sporadic. Intra-arterial chemo emerging; focal therapies preserve vision. 8. **Germ cell tumors** — different biology from adult; sacrococcygeal teratoma classic neonatal. 9. **CNS** — most common pediatric cancer; medulloblastoma + ependymoma + various gliomas + ATRT + craniopharyngioma. Treatment modifications by age + risk. **Pediatric oncology principles**: - Multidisciplinary teams - Risk-adapted therapy - Clinical trial enrollment (high % in pediatric) - Reduce late effects (de-escalate when feasible based on better risk stratification) - Family + child-centered care - Long-term follow-up + survivorship - Specialized pediatric oncology centers (Children''s Oncology Group sites). **Tumor biology** distinct: fewer mutations overall, often translocations or copy number changes driving disease; epigenetic + transcription factor-driven. Increasing precision oncology — pediatric MATCH + APEC etc. trials testing molecularly-targeted approaches.', NULL,
  'hard', 'pediatrics', 'review',
  'surgery', 'clinical_decision', 'pediatrics', 'child',
  'COG Children''s Oncology Group; NCCN Pediatric Tumors; INRG Neuroblastoma; SIOP Wilms', 'AI-generated-board-seed', true, 'seeded via Claude Code session (no critique pass)'
